**F1 — `tx.preview()` does not exist, and is nearly free to add.** `Transaction::new` builds `working: Graph<C>` as a full clone of the graph (`transaction.rs:38`). Every staging and recompute step runs against `self.working`. The real graph is untouched until the *very last line* of `commit()`: `std::mem::swap(self.graph, &mut self.working)` (`transaction.rs:285`). `Drop` just clears `transaction_open` (`transaction.rs:302`) — a dropped, uncommitted transaction discards the working copy cleanly. **So a dry run is: run the commit pipeline, build the `TransactionResult`, and return it *without the swap*.** The clone is already paid. There is no `preview`/`dry_run` in the tree today (grep-confirmed). This is real, small, and the keystone the first design missed — it is upstream ask #1.
 [...] ```rust
impl<'graph, C: Clone + PartialEq> Transaction<'graph, C> {
    /// Runs the full commit pipeline on the working copy and returns the
    /// TransactionResult WITHOUT writing back to the graph. The transaction is
    /// consumed; the real graph is untouched. Nearly free — the working clone
    /// is already paid at `begin_transaction`.
    pub fn preview(mut self) -> GraphResult<TransactionResult<C>>;
}
```

Implementation is `commit()` minus the final `std::mem::swap` and minus mutating the *real* graph's audit state (record audit onto `working` so the returned result carries explanations, then drop `working`). ~30 lines, reusing the existing pipeline. I will draft this PR against `~/src/trellis` and its test (`preview_does_not_mutate_graph`, `preview_result_equals_commit_result_then_discard`) as the opening move — it is the cleanest possible "tenex-edge feeds Trellis" artifact. [...] **Tested (beyond the shipped unit tests):** I wrote a fresh demonstration on a **resource-owning graph modeled on tenex-edge's real use case** — a set of channels driving one relay-subscription Open/Close each — and ran it. It proved all four properties of a true dry-run:

| Step | Result |
|---|---|
| `preview(drop "random")` | returns `[Close(sub:random)]` — the plan a commit *would* emit |
| graph after preview | **unchanged**: `random` still open, `Revision(1)` unchanged, input still `{general, random}` |
| `preview(add "ops")` from the *same* state | a *different* plan `[Open(sub:ops)]`; `ops` not opened, revision still 1 — previews are independent and apply nothing |
| `commit(drop "random")` | plan **equals** the earlier preview; `random` now actually CLOSED; revision advanced |

So `preview()` is genuinely the "what would committing this fact produce?" simulation — the plan you'd get, with zero mutation to the live graph — which is exactly what Phase 1's `probe simulate` and the safety invariant are built on. The throwaway demo and the merged worktree/branch are cleaned up.

The keystone is now real and landed upstream. Phase 1 slice [#233](https://github.com/pablof7z/tenex-edge/issues/233) (wire `tx.preview()` → `probe simulate`) is unblocked whenever you want to start building the frontier program.
